<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911127-0055</DOCNO><DOCID>911127-0055.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Ford Motor Co.:   Firm to Spend $700 Million   On Converting Axle Plant</HL><DATE>11/27/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><CO>   F U.FRD</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><RE>EUROPE (EU)MICHIGAN (MI)NORTH AMERICA (NME)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Ford Motor Co. said it will spend $700 million to equipits Van Dyke axle plant in Sterling Heights, Mich., toproduce a new transmission.   Conversion of the plant will begin early next year withproduction scheduled to start in 1994. The move is the latestexample of heavy spending by the Dearborn, Mich., auto makerto upgrade its engines and transmission.</LP><TEXT>   Separately, Ford said it is transferring ownership of itsJaguar luxury car unit to its Ford of Europe unit from itsFord of Great Britain unit. Jaguar, which had a $100 millionloss for the third quarter, will continue to report to L.Lindsey Halstead, chairman of Ford of Europe.   The move &quot;doesn't reflect any changes in Jaguar's plansnor its strategies,&quot; a Ford spokesman said. The move is beingmade for tax reasons, according to a company executive. Fordbought Jaguar, based in Coventry, England, in early 1990 for$2.5 billion.</TEXT></DOC>